    <stitle>VT 275 Engine Diagnostics Manual - Electronic Control Systems Diagnostics - Circuit Diagnostics - ECM PWR
        (Electronic Control Module Power)
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc id="s305010706.14" svcproctype="diagnose" graphiccount="4">
        <title>ECM PWR (Electronic Control Module Power)</title>
        <svcprocinfo id="s305010706.14.1">
            <figure id="f305010752" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figj31/j31085.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="472px"
                         scalefitheight="592px"/>
                <caption>Function diagram for the ECM PWR</caption>
            </figure>
            <para id="s305010706.13.1.1"></para>
            <table id="t3050107117" type="simple" frame="topbot">
                <title>The function diagram for ECM PWR includes the following:</title>
                <tgroup cols="1">
                    <colspec colname="col1" colwidth="1.0*"/>
                    <tbody>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Electronic Control Module (ECM)</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Battery</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>ECM power relay</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Ignition switch or Power relay</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Fuses</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                    </tbody>
                </tgroup>
            </table>
            <para>
                <title>Function</title>The Electronic Control Module (ECM) requires a 12 volt power source to function
                correctly. Operating power is received from the vehicle batteries through the ECM main power relay each
                time the ignition switch is turned ON.
            </para>
            <para>When the ignition switch is turned ON, the ECM provides an internal ground to the coil side of the ECM
                power relay. This closes the relay contacts and provides the ECM with power.
            </para>
        </svcprocinfo>
        <svcsubproc id="s305010706.14.2">
            <title>ECM PWR Circuit Operation</title>
            <figure id="f305010753" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figj31/j31086.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="472px"
                         scalefitheight="592px"/>
                <caption>ECM PWR circuit diagram</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>The ECM is grounded to the battery negative terminal at ECM terminals X3-6 and X3-7.</para>
            <para>When the ignition switch is turned on the ECM receives V
                <subscript>IGN</subscript>
                power at Pin X3-3. The power signals the ECM to provide a ground path to switch the ECM power relay from
                Pin X3-5 to relay Pin 2(85). Switching the ECM relay provides power directly from the battery positive
                terminal through two fuses and relay contacts 3(30) and 5(87) to Pins X4-1 and X4-2. See the applicable
                truck Circuit Diagram Manual for circuit numbers, connector and fuse locations.
            </para>
            <para>
                <title>Fault Detection/Management</title>The ECM internally monitors battery voltage. When the ECM
                continuously receives less than 7 volts or more than 23 volts, a Diagnostic Trouble Code (DTC) will be
                set.
            </para>
            <para>
                <title>ECM PWR DTCs</title>DTCs are read using the EST or by counting the flashes from the amber and red
                lamps.
            </para>
            <table id="t3050107118" type="simple" frame="topbot">
                <title>DTC 112</title>
                <tgroup cols="1">
                    <colspec colname="col1" colwidth="1.0*"/>
                    <tbody>
                        <row>
                            <entry>
                                <para>Electrical system voltage B+ out-of-range high</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>DTC 112 is set when the ECM detects an alternator output greater than 23 volts at
                                    PIN X3-3 for more than 0.5 seconds.
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>DTC 112 can be set when jump starting the engine and additional voltage is
                                    introduced. Incorrect external battery connections can cause the voltage increase.
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>If the condition causing DTC 112 is intermittent, the code will change from active
                                    to inactive status. DTC 112 will not cause the amber lamp (WEL for CF) to turn on.
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                    </tbody>
                </tgroup>
            </table>
            <table id="t3050107119" type="simple" frame="topbot">
                <title>DTC 113</title>
                <tgroup cols="1">
                    <colspec colname="col1" colwidth="1.0*"/>
                    <tbody>
                        <row>
                            <entry>
                                <para>Electrical system voltage B+ out-of-range low</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>DTC 113 is set when the ECM detects less than 7 volts at PIN X3-3 for more than
                                    0.5 seconds.
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>DTC 113 can be set by a failed alternator or ECM power relay, discharged
                                    batteries, or increased resistance in the battery feed circuits.
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>If the condition causing DTC 113 is intermittent, the code will change from active
                                    to inactive status. DTC 113 will not cause the amber lamp (WEL for CF) to turn on.
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                    </tbody>
                </tgroup>
            </table>
            <para>When DTC 112 or 113 is active, see the applicable truck Circuit Diagram Manual for circuit numbers,
                connector and fuse locations.
            </para>
            <table id="t3050107120" type="simple" frame="topbot">
                <title>DTC 626</title>
                <tgroup cols="1">
                    <colspec colname="col1" colwidth="1.0*"/>
                    <tbody>
                        <row>
                            <entry>
                                <para>Unexpected reset fault</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>DTC 626 is set when power is interrupted to the ECM. Loose or dirty connections at
                                    battery or ground cables can cause the ECM to power down.
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>After circuit becomes intact, the ECM will reboot. Erratic engine performance can
                                    occur. Turning engine ignition switch to OFF and then to ON will cause the code to
                                    change from active to inactive status.
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>When DTC 626 is active, monitor the voltage at ECM PIN X4-1 and X4-2. Examine for
                                    intermittent connections in the power feed wiring. The EST can be used to indicate
                                    DTCs and display the V
                                    <subscript>IGN</subscript>
                                    voltage measured by the ECM to PIN X3-3.
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>DTC 626 will not turn the amber lamp (WEL for CF) on.</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                    </tbody>
                </tgroup>
            </table>
